More news and notes on the traditional inter-administration
employment musical chairs within the D.C. media scene.

Dylan Byers ( https://puck.news/author/dylan-byers/?utm_campaign=3DIn+the+R=
oom+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F3%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%281%2F3%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_ter=
m=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Dylan Byers ( https://puck.news/author/dylan-byers/?utm_campaign=3DIn+the+R=
oom+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F3%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%281%2F3%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_ter=
m=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

This week, a team of editors at The Washington Post
sent a practically funereal note to their staff announcing the regrettable =
defection of one of their top young political journalists. After =E2=80=9Ca=
 remarkable, scoop-filled run as a White House reporter,=E2=80=9D Tyler Pag=
er had decided to take his talents five blocks west to The New York Times, =
where he will soon reunite with Matea Gold, the longtime Post managing edit=
or who also migrated to the Times last month after being passed over for
the Post=E2=80=99s top editor job. =E2=80=9CTyler=E2=80=99s loss will be ke=
enly felt in the Post newsroom,=E2=80=9D the paper=E2=80=99s national edito=
r Phil Rucker wrote, =E2=80=9Cbut we wish him the best in this new phase of=
 his career.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

The lavish praise heaped upon Pager, a skilled but modestly accomplished tw=
enty-something reporter, was at once a diplomatic farewell, a genuine expre=
ssion of loss, and, frankly, a
hunger scream from Post institutionalists who have been losing great report=
ers for years=E2=80=94Fahrenthold, Costa, Leibo in a previous lifetime, dit=
to Peter Baker=E2=80=94and are now witnessing another alarming post-electio=
n exodus. Since last week, when I reported on these impending defections, t=
he Post=E2=80=99s Ashley Parker and Michael Scherer have left for The Atlan=
tic, star
Trump reporter Josh Dawsey is still loose in the saddle and entertaining of=
fers from the paper=E2=80=99s competitors, and a host of other reporters ar=
e eyeing the exits. On the opinion side, several editors and columnists hav=
e also left the paper.

=C2=A0

Whatever you make of it, the Post=E2=80=99s brain drain reflects a true inf=
lection point for the storied
institution=E2=80=94and a decisive moment for its publisher Will Lewis and =
his hand-picked executive editor Matt Murray. (As I=E2=80=99ve reported ( h=
ttps://puck.news/matt-murray-to-be-named-washington-post-top-editor/?utm_ca=
mpaign=3DIn+the+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F3%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Ro=
om+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F3%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcu=
stomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), Lewis has decided to officially =
anoint Murray as editor, but has yet to announce it.) Lewis=E2=80=99s yearl=
ong tenure has been largely defined by mutual contempt between him and his =
newsroom, which he
rarely visits: He has been audibly impatient with their myopia and aversion=
 to change, at the same time that many reporters lament his brash demeanor =
and disregard for sacred Post customs, all while quietly suspecting that he=
 doesn=E2=80=99t really have a plan to save the paper. (An alternate theory=
: He does have a strategy but won=E2=80=99t reveal it for fear of another b=
out of upheaval. Alas, the outmoded economics of the newsroom businesses re=
quires this unhappy couple to remain married
despite seemingly irreconcilable differences.)=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Now, after naively and consistently thinking that Lewis would be forced to =
leave for all his sins=E2=80=94the Buzbee slight, the Murdoch stuff, the Fo=
lkenflik offense=E2=80=94only his uppermost talent are departing for greene=
r pastures. It=E2=80=99s a shitty situation, and one that was both entirely=
 avoidable
and yet nonetheless necessary. I=E2=80=99m not Dr. Phil, but it=E2=80=99s u=
nhealthy to despise your colleagues.

=C2=A0

Lewis anticipated, and certainly welcomes, some of this post-election turno=
ver, as I=E2=80=99ve noted before. The Post has spent years coddling journa=
lists who were just as responsible for its lackluster editorial product as =
the editors and operators they blamed for their misfortune. That said,
it=E2=80=99s hard to imagine that driving the most notable political report=
ers out of the building was really part of the plan. Stars like Dawsey and =
Parker had achieved pseudo-celebrity status in the first Trump term, and mi=
ght have been poised to recapture that fame in the next. (Although, to be h=
onest, a post-Trump ennui exists at both the Post and the Times. Maybe it=
=E2=80=99s time for a new generation to take over=E2=80=A6) In an early int=
erview with Semafor, Lewis described
Scherer as his favorite reporter at the paper (though he also had to search=
 for his name=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cred tie, glasses=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94s=
o maybe he was paying a little bit of lip service).

=C2=A0

Whatever the case, the mass migration of high-profile Posties, coupled with=
 Murray=E2=80=99s whispered coronation, likely marks the end of this highly=
 depressing internal blame game. Bezos won without stepping foot off
his yacht, the people who once defined the paper are leaving, and Lewis is =
now responsible for envisioning the next chapter with a new stable of talen=
t=E2=80=94and with only a few of his apparent nine lives available to him.=
=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The challenge, of course, is figuring out how to lure talent to a place tha=
t everyone seems to be leaving. And yet, as Posties know well, there is an =
excess of quality journalists in the market and a
paucity of jobs available. Lewis and Bezos may have screwed the pooch and a=
lienated plenty of the building, but they have many macroeconomic trends on=
 their side.

Poaching Politico
-----------------

Speaking of turnover, another notable D.C. media exodus
took place this week across the Potomac at Politico, where political report=
er Meridith McGraw, congressional reporter Olivia Beavers, and trade and ec=
onomics reporter Gavin Bade all jumped ship, at the same time, to The Wall =
Street Journal. Emma Tucker=E2=80=99s midnight raid on Politico speaks to t=
he endurance of the Journal=E2=80=99s own political reportage in the second=
 Trump term; after knocking her D.C. bureau down to the
studs, she is rebuilding it with younger and conveniently less expensive ta=
lent. (And if you=E2=80=99re engaged in that sort of Washington rebuilding =
effort, where else to poach from but Politico, the traditional D.C. feeder =
academy?)

=C2=A0

At the same time, the Politico defections, which come on the heels of a doz=
en or so other departures in the last year, highlight that newsroom=E2=80=
=99s enduring aimlessness in its core
Washington coverage. Notably, the McGraw defection leaves Politico without =
a super well-sourced Trump reporter, as its incoming White House bureau chi=
ef Dasha Burns was primarily on the DeSantis beat during the 2024 cycle. (M=
cGraw appears to have felt big-footed by the Dasha hire; time will tell whe=
ther Politico made the right tradeoff, but their second-coming-of-Jesus rol=
lout likely didn=E2=80=99t help.)

=C2=A0

Politico remains a formidable, very profitable business thanks largely to i=
ts policy-focused mega-expensive enterprise subscription business and its t=
rans-Atlantic expansion. But its own forfeiture of agenda-setting politics =
coverage=E2=80=94which has been a reality for years=E2=80=94is no less rema=
rkable than the diminished fortunes of the Post, itself.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

What
gives? Of late, there=E2=80=99s been a fair amount of internal finger point=
ing within that institution, as well. Several journalists have blamed co-fo=
under John Harris and his Kushneresque news chief Alex Burns for an exactin=
g and sometimes overbearing editing process in which Burns seems barely abl=
e to mask his annoyance with his reporters=E2=80=99 copy. Presumably, manag=
ement feels like it wouldn=E2=80=99t have to be so overbearing if the repor=
ters were able to meet the bar on their
own. More generally, there seems to be a lack of clarity about Politico=E2=
=80=99s editorial mission in an arena where the Times sets the agenda, Axio=
s publishes a half a dozen alarm-emoji-inflected daily microscoops, and Pun=
chbowl eats everyone=E2=80=99s lunch on a quotidian basis on the Hill. Poli=
tico leadership perpetually signals that it is on the cusp of a transformat=
ion, but whatever moves are coming will need to be more transformative than=
 a few rudimentary off-season hires.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

In recent weeks, a rumor has taken hold in the Politico newsroom that Burns=
 may soon be moving back to New York. There=E2=80=99s no truth to it yet, I=
=E2=80=99m told, but perhaps it speaks to the broader discontent, and a hop=
e that the status quo might soon change. If true, that would potentially fo=
rce Harris=E2=80=94an accomplished and avuncular mentor type, but not quite=
 the visionary peer to his Axios stepbrothers=E2=80=94to find a
new princeling to enforce his vision so he can reign as the paterfamilias.

Meanwhile, of course, this sort of talent leakage is nothing new for the co=
mpany, which previously survived the departures of Mike Allen and Maggie Ha=
berman and Ben Smith, among so many others. Indeed, under the stewardship o=
f Axel Springer, it may believe, like the Post, that its future is based mo=
re than ever on its
brand rather than its star talent, and the joke is on us for caring. After =
all, the Journal deprives stars of their voice. The Times, for its part, ha=
s become such a parking lot for talent that, with the notable exception of =
Haberman, few have been able to meaningfully differentiate themselves upon =
arrival. Recall that Axel=E2=80=99s other principal U.S. holdings include I=
nsider and Morning Brew. Quick: Name your favorite journalists at one of th=
ose places. That=E2=80=99s
what I thought=E2=80=A6

