=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">This week, a team of editors at <em>The Wa=
shington Post
</em>sent a practically funereal note to their staff announcing the regrett=
able defection of one of their top young political journalists. After =E2=
=80=9Ca remarkable, scoop-filled run as a White House reporter,=E2=80=9D <s=
trong>Tyler Pager </strong>had decided to take his talents five blocks west=
 to <em>The New York Times</em>, where he will soon reunite with <strong>Ma=
tea Gold</strong>, the longtime <em>Post </em>managing editor who also migr=
ated to the <em>Times </em>last month after being passed over for
the <em>Post</em>=E2=80=99s top editor job. =E2=80=9CTyler=E2=80=99s loss w=
ill be keenly felt in the <em>Post</em> newsroom,=E2=80=9D the paper=E2=80=
=99s national editor <strong>Phil Rucker</strong> wrote, =E2=80=9Cbut we wi=
sh him the best in this new phase of his career.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;">The lavish praise heaped upon Pager, a skilled but modestly accomplished=
 twenty-something reporter, was at once a diplomatic farewell, a genuine ex=
pression of loss, and, frankly, a
hunger scream from <em>Post </em>institutionalists who have been losing gre=
at reporters for years=E2=80=94<strong>Fahrenthold</strong>, <strong>Costa<=
/strong>, <strong>Leibo </strong>in a previous lifetime, ditto <strong>Pete=
r Baker=E2=80=94</strong>and are now witnessing another alarming post-elect=
ion exodus. Since last week, when I reported on these impending defections,=
 the <em>Post</em>=E2=80=99s <strong>Ashley Parker </strong>and <strong>Mic=
hael Scherer </strong>have left for <em>The Atlantic</em>, star
<strong>Trump</strong> reporter <strong>Josh Dawsey </strong>is still loose=
 in the saddle and entertaining offers from the paper=E2=80=99s competitors=
, and a host of other reporters are eyeing the exits. On the opinion side, =
<em>several </em>editors and columnists have also left the paper.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">Whatever you make of it, the <em>Post</em>=E2=80=99s brain drain=
 reflects a true inflection point for the storied
institution=E2=80=94and a decisive moment for its publisher <strong>Will Le=
wis </strong>and his hand-picked executive editor <strong>Matt Murray</stro=
ng>. (As I=E2=80=99ve <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZC=
I6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVTGtwbWdDcFB0QXhqSE43ekhncz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0c=
HM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvbWF0dC1tdXJyYXktdG8tYmUtbmFtZWQtd2FzaGluZ3Rvbi1wb3N0LXRv=
cC1lZGl0b3IvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1Jbit0aGUrUm9vbSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODElMkY=
zJTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1JbitUaGUrUm9vbSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyOD=
ElMkYzJTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY=
2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5h=
bCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIwMjQ2Mjl9/d47470d38e48b5bd60=
9902e444444f98a80377300d789623db0871ef263f4433" style=3D"text-decoration:un=
derline;color:#d40000;">reported</a>, Lewis <em>has </em>decided to officia=
lly anoint Murray as editor, but has yet to announce it.) Lewis=E2=80=99s y=
earlong tenure has been largely defined by mutual contempt between him and =
his newsroom, which he
rarely visits: He has been audibly impatient with their myopia and aversion=
 to change, at the same time that many reporters lament his brash demeanor =
and disregard for sacred <em>Post </em>customs, all while quietly suspectin=
g that he doesn=E2=80=99t <em>really</em> have a plan to save the paper. (A=
n alternate theory: He does have a strategy but won=E2=80=99t reveal it for=
 fear of another bout of upheaval. Alas, the outmoded economics of the news=
room businesses requires this unhappy couple to remain married
despite seemingly irreconcilable differences.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">No=
w, after naively and consistently thinking that <em>Lewis</em> would be for=
ced to leave for all his sins=E2=80=94the <strong>Buzbee</strong> slight, t=
he <strong>Murdoch</strong> <em>stuff</em>, the <strong>Folkenflik</strong>=
 offense=E2=80=94only his uppermost talent are departing for greener pastur=
es. It=E2=80=99s a shitty situation, and one that was both entirely avoidab=
le
and yet nonetheless necessary. I=E2=80=99m not <strong>Dr. Phil</strong>, b=
ut it=E2=80=99s unhealthy to despise your colleagues.</p><p style=3D"margin=
:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">L=
ewis anticipated, and certainly welcomes, some of this post-election turnov=
er, as I=E2=80=99ve noted before. The <em>Post </em>has spent years coddlin=
g journalists who were just as responsible for its lackluster editorial pro=
duct as the editors and operators they blamed for their misfortune. That sa=
id,
it=E2=80=99s hard to imagine that driving the <em>most</em> notable politic=
al reporters out of the building was really part of the plan. Stars like Da=
wsey and Parker had achieved pseudo-celebrity status in the first Trump ter=
m, and might have been poised to recapture that fame in the next. (Although=
, to be honest, a post-Trump ennui exists at both the <em>Post </em>and the=
 <em>Times</em>. Maybe it=E2=80=99s time for a new generation to take over=
=E2=80=A6) In an early interview with Semafor, Lewis described
Scherer as his <em>favorite</em> reporter at the paper (though he also had =
to search for his name=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cred tie, glasses=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D=
=E2=80=94so maybe he was paying a little bit of lip service).</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">Whatever the case, the mass migration of high-profile Posties, cou=
pled with Murray=E2=80=99s whispered coronation, likely marks the end of th=
is <em>highly </em>depressing internal blame game. <strong>Bezos</strong> w=
on without stepping foot off
his yacht, the people who once defined the paper are leaving, and Lewis is =
now responsible for envisioning the next chapter with a new stable of talen=
t=E2=80=94and with only a few of his apparent nine lives available to him.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;">The challenge, of course, is figuring out how to lure talent to a =
place that everyone seems to be leaving. And yet, as Posties know well, the=
re is an excess of quality journalists in the market and a
paucity of jobs available. Lewis and Bezos may have screwed the pooch and a=
lienated plenty of the building, but they have many macroeconomic trends on=
 their side.</p></div>
