line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Speaking of turnover, another notable D.C. medi=
a exodus
took place this week across the Potomac at Politico, where political report=
er <strong>Meridith McGraw</strong>, congressional reporter <strong>Olivia =
Beavers</strong>, and trade and economics reporter <strong>Gavin Bade </str=
ong>all jumped ship, at the same time, to <em>The Wall Street Journal. </em=
><strong>Emma Tucker</strong>=E2=80=99s midnight raid on Politico speaks to=
 the endurance of the <em>Journal</em>=E2=80=99s own political reportage in=
 the second Trump term; after knocking her D.C. bureau down to the
studs, she is rebuilding it with younger and conveniently less expensive ta=
lent. (And if you=E2=80=99re engaged in that sort of Washington rebuilding =
effort, where else to poach from but Politico, the traditional D.C. feeder =
academy?)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">At the same time, the Politico defections, wh=
ich come on the heels of a dozen or so other departures in the last year, h=
ighlight that newsroom=E2=80=99s enduring aimlessness in its core
Washington coverage. Notably, the McGraw defection leaves Politico without =
a super well-sourced Trump reporter, as its incoming White House bureau chi=
ef <strong>Dasha Burns </strong>was primarily on the <strong>DeSantis </str=
ong>beat during the 2024 cycle. (McGraw appears to have felt big-footed by =
the Dasha hire; time will tell whether Politico made the right tradeoff, bu=
t their second-coming-of-Jesus rollout likely didn=E2=80=99t help.)</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-=
bottom:0px;">Politico remains a formidable, very profitable business thanks=
 largely to its policy-focused mega-expensive enterprise subscription busin=
ess and its trans-Atlantic expansion. But its own forfeiture of agenda-sett=
ing politics coverage=E2=80=94which has been a reality for <em>years=E2=80=
=94</em>is no less remarkable than the diminished fortunes of the <em>Post<=
/em>, itself.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">What
gives? Of late, there=E2=80=99s been a fair amount of internal finger point=
ing within that institution, as well. Several journalists have blamed co-fo=
under <strong>John Harris </strong>and his Kushneresque news chief <strong>=
Alex Burns</strong> for an exacting and sometimes overbearing editing proce=
ss in which Burns seems barely able to mask his annoyance with his reporter=
s=E2=80=99 copy. Presumably, management feels like it wouldn=E2=80=99t have=
 to be so overbearing if the reporters were able to meet the bar on their
own. More generally, there seems to be a lack of clarity about Politico=E2=
=80=99s editorial mission in an arena where the <em>Times </em>sets the age=
nda, Axios publishes a half a dozen alarm-emoji-inflected daily microscoops=
, and Punchbowl eats everyone=E2=80=99s lunch on a quotidian basis on the H=
ill. Politico leadership perpetually signals that it is on the cusp of a tr=
ansformation, but whatever moves are coming will need to be more transforma=
tive than a few rudimentary off-season hires.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In =
recent weeks, a rumor has taken hold in the Politico newsroom that Burns ma=
y soon be moving back to New York. There=E2=80=99s no truth to it <em>yet</=
em>, I=E2=80=99m told, but perhaps it speaks to the broader discontent, and=
 a hope that the status quo might soon change. If true, that would potentia=
lly force Harris=E2=80=94an accomplished and avuncular mentor type, but not=
 quite the visionary peer to his Axios stepbrothers=E2=80=94to find a
new princeling to enforce his vision so he can reign as the <em>paterfamili=
as</em>.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Meanwhile, of course, this sort of =
talent leakage is nothing new for the company, which previously survived th=
e departures of <strong>Mike Allen</strong> and <strong>Maggie Haberman </s=
trong>and <strong>Ben Smith</strong>, among so many others. Indeed, under t=
he stewardship of Axel Springer, it may believe, like the <em>Post, </em>th=
at its future is based more than ever on its
<em>brand</em> rather than its star talent, and the joke is on us for carin=
g. After all, the <em>Journal </em>deprives stars of their voice. The <em>T=
imes</em>, for its part, has become such a parking lot for talent that, wit=
h the notable exception of Haberman, few have been able to meaningfully dif=
ferentiate themselves upon arrival. Recall that Axel=E2=80=99s <em>other</e=
m> principal U.S. holdings include Insider and Morning Brew. Quick: Name yo=
ur favorite journalists at one of those places. That=E2=80=99s
what I thought=E2=80=A6</p></div>
